This works because `T` gets inferred as an intersection type - `List&lt;User&gt; &amp; CacheResult &amp; Object`. After all, why can&#39;t a class both implement `List&lt;User&gt;` _and_ implement/extend `CacheResult`? Such a type is certainly possible!

You can see this happen by writing a toy program and using the `--debug=verboseResolution=all` option:

```
import java.util.List;

public class Main {

  public static void main(String[] args) {
    List&lt;User&gt; u = new Main().get();
  }

  public &lt;T extends CacheResult&gt; T get() {
    return null;
  }
}

interface CacheResult {}
class User implements CacheResult {}
```

`javac` with `verboseResolution=all` would output:

```
  instantiated signature: ()INT#1
  target-type: List&lt;User&gt;
  where T is a type-variable:
    T extends CacheResult declared in method &lt;T&gt;get()
  where INT#1 is an intersection type:
    INT#1 extends Object,List&lt;User&gt;,CacheResult
```

You can also follow through [the process of how Java does type inference](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se8/html/jls-18.html). Eventually (somewhere in &quot;resolution&quot;), you&#39;ll reach a point where you need to find the _greatest lower bound_ (&quot;glb&quot;) of `Object`, `List&lt;User&gt;` and `CacheResult`, and that type is exactly their intersection type, as defined [here](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se8/html/jls-5.html#jls-5.1.10).

On the other hand, your code won&#39;t compile if `CacheResult` is a class, and the type you are assigning the method result to is an unrelated class, since no class can inherit from two unrelated classes.

